What Are Needles & Syringes?
Needles and syringes are sterile disposable medical devices designed to administer medications, vaccines, biologics, and other therapeutic solutions through subcutaneous, intramuscular, or intravenous injection. They are also widely used for blood collection, diagnostic sampling, and laboratory applications.
A syringe generally consists of a barrel, plunger, piston, and push rod, while a needle includes the needle tube, hub, and beveled tip. Both components are connected through standardized interfaces such as Luer Lock or Luer Slip systems, ensuring accurate dosage delivery, leak-proof connections, and maximum patient safety.
Today, manufacturers are increasingly focusing on safety-engineered products that reduce needlestick injuries, improve injection accuracy, and support self-administration of medicines at home.
